Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["", "SlideShowNavigationBar",
 CellTags->
  "SlideShowHeader",ExpressionUUID->"738ea7bb-46e7-4da0-8f33-6e66dfbcf94f"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Importing Data: Excel-XLS", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.5722540746219873`*^9, 3.572254078460119*^9}, {
  3.57347085338712*^9, 
  3.573470860940666*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7714aaad-a92d-4ada-9c93-\
c044eb804076"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Data can be brought into the Wolfram Language using the ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["Import",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:ref/Import"],
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " function. A variety of formats are supported, but this course focuses on \
Excel and comma- or tab-separated values. In these examples the ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["SetDirectory",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:ref/SetDirectory"],
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " approach to organizing files is used. This is done in the initialization \
cell where the directory is set."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.5722542289043083`*^9, 3.572254318480649*^9}, {
   3.572254390785643*^9, 3.572254392194046*^9}, {3.573213750942642*^9, 
   3.573213813893153*^9}, 3.5734702575557137`*^9, {3.5735492348477697`*^9, 
   3.573549250708749*^9}, 3.577201507838497*^9, 3.5800310744083157`*^9, {
   3.5800311122592487`*^9, 3.58003113540031*^9}, {3.5801470591889157`*^9, 
   3.5801470910338078`*^9}, 3.580217780999578*^9, {3.6316435698426943`*^9, 
   3.631643653124262*^9}, {3.63266383391244*^9, 
   3.632663838859825*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"32917d12-3fa2-4841-8dde-\
7cf0698bcc00"],

Cell["\<\
It is prudent once you have the file contents in the Wolfram Language to look \
at the data to see if it is in a form that can be used for analysis. It is \
possible to bring a file into the Wolfram Language only to find you have one \
long string. This is not going to be useful for analysis, unless you are \
analyzing sentence structures or something of that sort. This section looks \
at various issues that can arise and illustrates some methods of avoiding the \
problems. Examples are also given of how to manipulate the data to get it in \
a form suitable for investigations.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.57347051196591*^9, 3.573470678361255*^9}, {
   3.573470726425921*^9, 3.5734708248198223`*^9}, 3.573978873644375*^9, {
   3.580031187648431*^9, 3.580031188351347*^9}, {3.580031231967136*^9, 
   3.5800312836686897`*^9}, {3.580147129224382*^9, 3.5801471315292473`*^9}, {
   3.622382289207072*^9, 3.622382304387287*^9}, {3.622394658345359*^9, 
   3.622394707925086*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"60a6022c-330f-4883-9e30-\
f791b953bbe8"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Excel Files", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.577201542547813*^9, 
  3.577201546837699*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ed21e0b3-b1cb-492d-893e-\
a872f1caacad"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Excel files consist of one or more sheets. With the default behavior, the \
Wolfram Language",
 StyleBox[" ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "will bring in all the sheets as a list of arrays. In the first example, an \
entire file is brought in, with the older extension ",
 ButtonBox["XLS",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:ref/Format/XLS"],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.572254476411639*^9, 3.572254480267836*^9}, {
   3.572254807508409*^9, 3.572254890155323*^9}, {3.5722577561409693`*^9, 
   3.5722577561438303`*^9}, 3.5722578181796923`*^9, {3.572257862545891*^9, 
   3.572257882082941*^9}, {3.57225791731479*^9, 3.572257939315538*^9}, {
   3.572257988132707*^9, 3.572257991100554*^9}, {3.5772015510614157`*^9, 
   3.577201585901967*^9}, {3.577201616319685*^9, 3.577201616655199*^9}, {
   3.5772016570342617`*^9, 3.577201657076669*^9}, {3.580031313534252*^9, 
   3.580031335612912*^9}, {3.622382320034409*^9, 3.6223823216024117`*^9}, {
   3.622394716078754*^9, 
